  "text": "## E0505 Error Generation Flow\n\nThe E0505 error (\"cannot move out of x because it is borrowed\") is generated through a multi-layered chain in the Rust compiler's MIR-based borrow checker:\n\n### 1. MIR Borrow Checker Core (`compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/lib.rs`)\n\nThe MirBorrowckCtxt struct (line 714) implements a ResultsVisitor that traverses the MIR in all statements and terminators. Key functions:\n- **visit_after_early_statement_effect** (line 787): Visitor entry point that processes statements\n- **consume_operand** (line 1706): Handles move operations. When an Operand::Move is encountered, it calls access_place with WriteKind::Move (line 1740)\n- **access_place** (line 1170): Checks access permissions and calls check_access_for_conflict\n- **check_access_for_conflict** (line 1246): Core borrow conflict detection. Uses each_borrow_involving_path to iterate active borrows and match read/write patterns\n\nAt line 1324-1362, when a Write(WriteKind::Move) pattern is detected against an active borrow, the code calls report_move_out_while_borrowed (line 1362), triggering the E0505 error.\n\nThe WriteKind enum (line 1096) defines WriteKind::Move as one of the access types tracked during borrow checking.\n\n### 2. Dataflow Analysis (`compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/dataflow.rs`)\n\nThe Borrowck struct (line 22) implements the Analysis trait and drives the dataflow computation that determines which borrows are active at each program point.\n\n### 3. Move-While-Borrowed Error Formatting (`compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/diagnostics/conflict_errors.rs`)\n\nThe **report_move_out_while_borrowed** function (line 1533) formats the diagnostic for the move-while-borrowed violation:\n- Retrieves borrow spans to point to where the borrow was created\n- Calls cannot_move_when_borrowed to create the error\n- Adds explanation context about why the borrow is still active\n- Suggests cloning if applicable\n\n### 4. Error Creation (`compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/borrowck_errors.rs`)\n\nThe **cannot_move_when_borrowed** method (line 16) creates an error using the session_diagnostics::MoveBorrow struct, which is tagged with code E0505.\n\n### 5. Session Diagnostics (`compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/session_diagnostics.rs`)\n\nThe **MoveBorrow** struct (line 286) is decorated with #[diag(borrowck_cannot_move_when_borrowed, code = E0505)], establishing the error code and message template.\n\n### 6. Error Code Definition (`compiler/rustc_error_codes/src/error_codes/E0505.md`)\n\nDefines the human-readable explanation and examples for E0505, including the error message template: \"A value was moved out while it was still borrowed.\"\n\n## Summary of the Detection Chain:\n\n1. MIR visitor processes statements/terminators\n2. Operand::Move detection triggers consume_operand\n3. access_place called with WriteKind::Move\n4. check_access_for_conflict detects conflict with active borrows\n5. report_move_out_while_borrowed called to format error\n6. cannot_move_when_borrowed creates E0505 diagnostic\n7. MoveBorrow struct renders the final error message\n\nThis design separates concerns: the borrow checker core identifies violations, conflict detection determines error types, and diagnostics handle formatting and user-facing messages."
}

